Why Are You Getting This Error?
The error "No process is on the other end of the pipe" usually happens because SQL Server is not allowing the login from Azure Data Factory. Hereâ€™s whatâ€™s likely causing the issue and how to fix it.

âœ… Step-by-Step Fix
1ï¸âƒ£ Make Sure SQL Server Authentication is Enabled
By default, SQL Server only allows Windows Authentication. Since you are using a SQL login (lahari), you need to enable SQL Server Authentication.

ðŸ›  How to Enable SQL Authentication:
Open SQL Server Management Studio (SSMS) and connect to HELLO\SQLEXPRESS.
Right-click on the server name (HELLO\SQLEXPRESS) â†’ Select "Properties".
Go to the "Security" tab.
Under "Server authentication", select "SQL Server and Windows Authentication mode".
Click OK and restart SQL Server:
Open Services.msc
Find SQL Server (SQLEXPRESS)
Right-click and Restart
ðŸ”„ Test again in ADF after this step.
2ï¸âƒ£ Check If Your User (lahari) Has Proper Permissions
Even if SQL Authentication is enabled, the user lahari might not have permission to log in.

ðŸ›  How to Grant Access to lahari:
In SSMS, go to Security â†’ Logins.
Right-click on lahari â†’ Select "Properties".
Go to "Server Roles" â†’ Check sysadmin (for full access, or public + db_owner for limited access).
Go to "User Mapping" â†’ Make sure lahari has access to AdventureWorksLT2022.
Click OK and try again.
3ï¸âƒ£ Ensure TCP/IP is Enabled in SQL Server Configuration
Since ADF runs on your self-hosted integration runtime, it needs to communicate over TCP/IP, not Named Pipes.

ðŸ›  How to Enable TCP/IP:
Open SQL Server Configuration Manager.
Expand SQL Server Network Configuration â†’ Click Protocols for SQLEXPRESS.
Right-click "TCP/IP" â†’ Click "Enable".
Restart SQL Server Service (again from Services.msc).
ðŸ”„ Try the connection again in ADF.

4ï¸âƒ£ Check Windows Firewall and Allow Port 1433
Even if everything is configured, your Windows firewall might be blocking ADFâ€™s access.

ðŸ›  How to Open Port 1433 for SQL Server:
Open Windows Defender Firewall â†’ Click Advanced Settings.
Go to Inbound Rules â†’ Click New Rule.
Select Port â†’ Click Next.
Choose TCP â†’ Type 1433 in "Specific local ports" â†’ Click Next.
Select Allow the connection â†’ Click Next.
Apply to Domain, Private, and Public â†’ Click Next.
Name it SQL Server 1433 â†’ Click Finish.
ðŸ”„ Test again in ADF.

ðŸ›  Final Troubleshooting Steps
If the error still persists, try these:
âœ… In ADF, change HELLO\SQLEXPRESS to 127.0.0.1,1433 (forcing TCP/IP).
âœ… Ensure SQL Browser Service is running in Services.msc.
âœ… Manually create the login again in SQL:

